SIMPLE: scrutiny
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scrutiny
<hw>Scru"ti*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>scrutinium</ets>, fr. <ets>scrutari</ets> to search carefully,
originally, to search even to the rags, fr. <ets>scruta</ets> trash,
trumpery; perhaps akin to E. <ets>shred</ets>: cf. AS.
<ets>scrudnian</ets> to make scrutiny.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Close
examination; minute inspection; critical observation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that have designed exactness and deep <qex>scrutiny</qex>
have taken some one part of nature.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thenceforth I thought thee worth my nearer view⟦br⟧
And narrower <qex>scrutiny</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Church)</fld> <def>An examination of
catechumens, in the last week of Lent, who were to receive baptism on
Easter Day.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Canon Law)</fld> <def>A ticket, or little paper
billet, on which a vote is written.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Parliamentary Practice)</fld> <def>An examination
by a committee of the votes given at an election, for the purpose of
correcting the poll.</def> <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrutiny</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scrutiny
<hw>Scru"ti*ny</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To scrutinize.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrutoire</ent>⟦br⟧
